Scope and Limitations of the Study
          This study focuses on developing a Supply and Construction Development Monitoring System specifically for Sunshine Sapphire Construction and Supply, Inc. It covers real-time project tracking, supply management, reporting, and safety monitoring for both private and government projects. However, the system is limited to the company’s current operations, 12-person workforce, existing Excel-based data, and available technology. It is designed for internal use and may require adjustments for other organizations or future company expansion.
   Scope
      This study focuses on developing a Supply and Construction Development Monitoring System for Sunshine Sapphire Construction and Supply, Inc. It aims to improve current Excel-based processes by providing real-time project monitoring, supply chain and inventory tracking, automated reporting, safety compliance, and communication tools. The system is designed to streamline construction operations—both private and government—while integrating features like KPI tracking, early warning alerts, and regulatory monitoring tailored to the company’s needs. The project will cover operations in Bacolod City and apply to all company departments, including engineering, admin, and on-site personnel.
   Limitation of the Study
       This study focuses on developing a customized supply chain management and integrated monitoring system for Sunshine Sapphire Construction and Supply, Inc., aimed at addressing inefficiencies in their current operations. The company presently relies on a manual, Excel-based process for monitoring construction development, which makes it difficult to manage multiple projects, results in delayed reporting, and lacks automation and real-time data access. The proposed system introduces features such as real-time tracking, automated reporting, and intelligent notifications to streamline operations and improve decision-making.
         However, the study is limited in several ways. While it lays the groundwork for digital transformation, it does not fully explore integration with existing business software such as accounting systems, supplier databases, or project management platforms. Many construction firms depend on such tools, and the lack of detailed compatibility analysis could pose challenges during system implementation. Furthermore, although the importance of employee adoption is acknowledged, the study does not develop in-depth training modules or change management strategies. Effective implementation requires staff buy-in and proper onboarding—areas not fully addressed in this research.
          Additionally, the study primarily focuses on the system’s initial development and short-term deployment within the constraints of a capstone project. It does not delve deeply into long-term system maintenance, technical support, or the regular updates needed to keep the system sustainable and scalable. These limitations highlight that, while the system offers meaningful improvements over manual Excel-based methods, further research and development will be necessary to ensure its full integration, long-term usability, and widespread adoption across the organization.
