Operational Definition of Terms
The operational definitions provided herein are meant to make clear and consistent reference of terms throughout this study. These terms are defined regarding the specific application of the term within this proposed system and the hardware and construction supply industry. These operational definitions set a basis for the common understanding of various technical concepts, system components, and business processes rigorously relevant to the development and evaluation of the Supply and Construction Development Monitoring. These terms are defined as per their respective applicability to the design, analysis, and implementation framework of this study.
Automated Reporting: The system's capability to generate project reports, progress updates, and compliance documents automatically without manual intervention, using standardized templates and formats to ensure consistency and completeness.
 Construction Safety Officer: A certified professional responsible for ensuring safety protocols and procedures are followed on construction sites, conducting safety meetings and tool-box meetings, and maintaining overall site safety standards.
Department of Public Works and Highways (DPWH): The government agency responsible for the planning, design, construction, and maintenance of infrastructure facilities in the Philippines, serving as one of Sunshine Sapphire's key government clients.
Early Warning System: A system feature designed to identify potential project issues and problems before they become critical, supporting proactive project management and decision-making processes.
First Aider: A trained individual present on construction sites who can provide immediate medical assistance in case of accidents or health emergencies, working in coordination with the Construction Safety Officer.
Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) Measurable values that demonstrate how effectively the company is achieving key business objectives, specifically focusing on on-time project completion rates and resource utilization as identified by Sunshine Sapphire.
Licensed Civil Engineer: A professional engineer licensed to practice civil engineering in the Philippines, responsible for structural and civil design services within the company's technical staff.
Local Government Units (LGUs): Local government entities in the Philippines including municipal, city, and provincial governments that commission construction projects and serve as key clients for Sunshine Sapphire.
Philippine Contractors Accreditation Board (PCAB): The government agency responsible for the registration and classification of construction contractors in the Philippines, requiring ongoing compliance from companies like Sunshine Sapphire.
Professional Electrical Engineer: A licensed professional responsible for electrical systems design and implementation in construction projects, forming part of the company's technical staff.
Professional Mechanical Engineer: A licensed professional responsible for mechanical systems design and implementation in construction projects, part of the company's technical staff.
Project Management: The application of knowledge, skills, tools, and techniques to project activities to meet project requirements and objectives, currently managed through Excel-based systems at Sunshine Sapphire.
Real-time Data Monitoring: The continuous tracking and updating of project information, supply chain status, and resource allocation as events occur, addressing the company's current limitation of not having access to current, real-time data.
Resource Utilization: The efficient use of human resources, materials, equipment, and financial resources in construction projects, currently tracked as one of the company's key performance indicators.
Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC): The government agency responsible for regulating the securities market and corporations in the Philippines, where Sunshine Sapphire was registered on November 14, 2019.
Supply Chain Management: The management of the flow of goods and services from suppliers to the construction site, including inventory control and procurement processes, currently managed through Excel-based systems
System Integration: The process of connecting different computing systems and software applications to act as a coordinated whole, replacing the current fragmented approach using separate Excel files and manual communication methods.
Tool-box Meeting: Regular safety meetings conducted on construction sites to discuss safety procedures, potential hazards, and safety protocols with workers before beginning work activities.


