FOREIGN LITERATURE
Construction Supply Chain: A Systematic Literature Review with Bibliometric Analysis (2024).
          According to the study by Singh et al. (2024), the paper systematically reviews the construction supply chain (CSC), focusing on its relationship with information technology, collaboration, performance measurement, and supply chain configuration. The study identifies research gaps in areas such as financial management, supply chain resilience, logistics, and vendor-managed inventory. It emphasizes the evolution of CSC standards and proposes future research directions aimed at enhancing supply chain management, which is vital for effective construction supplies monitoring.
Sustainable supply chain management in construction: An exploratory review for future research (2022).
          According to the study by Cataldo et al. (2022), this exploratory review investigates sustainable supply chain management (SSCM) in construction, emphasizing recent trends and future research directions. The research highlights the increasing adoption of sustainability practices, including life cycle assessment, green construction waste disposal, and collaborative project delivery. It underscores the importance of integrating sustainability into supply chain and materials monitoring to improve environmental and operational performance in construction projects.
A literature review on construction project success evaluation criteria and methods (2024).
          According to the study by Beshah et al. (2024), the research emphasizes the importance of stakeholder-responsive success criteria and evaluation methods in construction projects. It highlights how monitoring progress and managing supplies effectively are critical components of project success. The study underscores that implementing robust monitoring systems ensures timely material availability and maintains quality control, which are essential for achieving overall project objectives.
Automatic Monitoring Innovations for Construction Safety and Progress: A Review (2024). 
          According to the study by Muhammad Ali Musarat et al. (2024), this review focuses on innovations in automatic monitoring technologies that enhance safety and progress tracking in construction. It discusses the integration of Building Information Modeling (BIM), Internet of Things (IoT), and Artificial Intelligence (AI) for real-time monitoring of materials, equipment, and workforce, thereby improving overall construction development monitoring.

