CHAPTER III

DESIGN AND METHODOLOGY
      
          This chapter discusses the research approach and development methodology used in creating the Supply and Construction Development Monitoring System. It also presents the system design, specifications, and development process.
      
Research Approach
       In analyzing and designing the system, the proponents employed the Agile Software Development Method, which uses iterative cycles called sprints to deliver and refine functional features. This method emphasizes flexibility, adaptability, and continuous improvement, making it suitable for gradually integrating system functions and ensuring early delivery of essential features.
System Development Method
Figure 1. Agile Model
      The agile methodology will be implemented through the following phase:
Requirements
         In Agile, requirements are not gathered all at once but are continuously identified and refined throughout development. Instead of rigid documentation, requirements are broken down into user stories or backlog items that describe what the system should achieve from the user’s perspective. This makes the process flexible and ensures that the system always aligns with the users’ current needs.
Design
          The design phase in Agile is not fixed at the beginning but evolves with the project. The system is structured in a way that allows modifications as new requirements emerge. Agile design emphasizes simplicity and adaptability, ensuring that future changes or new features can be integrated without disrupting the entire system.
Development
          Development in Agile is carried out in short, time-boxed cycles called sprints. Each sprint delivers a set of working features that can be tested and used immediately. This incremental approach ensures that progress is visible and functional software is consistently delivered, reducing risks of delays or failures at the end of the project.
Testing
          Testing is integrated into every sprint, ensuring that issues are identified and corrected early rather than waiting until the end of development. This continuous testing approach maintains system quality, prevents accumulation of bugs, and guarantees that each new feature works correctly with the existing functions.
Deployment
          In Agile, deployment happens frequently and incrementally. Instead of waiting for the entire system to be finished, completed features are deployed in stages. This allows users to start benefiting from the system early, while developers continue adding improvements and new functionalities in future sprints.
Review
          The review stage takes place at the end of each sprint. Developers, along with users, evaluate the work completed, provide feedback, and identify what can be improved. This process ensures that the system remains aligned with user expectations and that future sprints are more efficient and better focused.



